      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 32:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and strangulation. The latter, though not named in Scripture, is regarded by the rabbis as the most common, and the proper one to be adopted when no other is expressly enjoined by the Law. Suspension, whether from cross, stake, or gallows, was not used as a mode of taking life, but was sometimes added after death as an enhancement of punishment. Pharaoh's chief baker ",
